Here's the pattern using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** â€” override `CreateWindow` and use a custom `Window` subclass:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell)
        {
            var notePage = shell.CurrentPage as NotePageView;
            notePage?.ViewModel.RestoreDraft();
        }
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Page is AppShell shell)
        {
            var notePage = shell.CurrentPage as NotePageView;
            notePage?.ViewModel.SaveDraft();
        }
    }
}
```

**In your ViewModel:**

```csharp
public class NoteViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;
    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set { _draftText = value; OnPropertyChanged(); }
    }

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", DraftText);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    // Call RestoreDraft() in constructor too, for cold starts
    public NoteViewModel() => RestoreDraft();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** â€” fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnDestroying`** â€” also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped` entirely.
- **`OnResumed`** â€” fires when returning from background (not on first launch).
- **Constructor** â€” handles cold-start restore since `Resumed` doesn't fire on initial launch.
- **Keep handlers fast** â€” `Preferences` is ideal for small values. Avoid DB writes or network calls in lifecycle handlers (Android enforces a ~5s ANR timeout).
